		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/arts/blueroom/blueroom-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/arts/blueroom/blueroom-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/arts/blueroom/blueroom-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002894321" width="592" height="320" alt="Mathieu Amalric with LÃ©a Drucker in &quot;The Blue Room.&quot;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Mathieu Amalric with LÃ©a Drucker in "The Blue Room."</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alfama Films</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/22/cannes-film-festival-a-belgian-thriller-by-way-of-france/" data-title="Cannes Film Festival: A Belgian Thriller by Way of France" data-description="The actor and director Mathieu Amalric adapted a Georges Simenon novel for his second submission to the festival.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">CANNES â On a rooftop terrace here this week, the actor and director Mathieu Amalric pulled a frayed robins-egg blue paperback out of his pocket. It was âLa Chambre Bleue,â or âThe Blue Room,â a thriller by Georges Simenon that the actor-director has just adapted for <a href="//www.festival-cannes.com/fr/archives/ficheFilm/id/100005442/year/2014.html">his film</a> in competition here in the Un Certain Regard section.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI had read the book because everyone in France falls on Simenon,â said Mr. Amalric, best known for his performances in âThe Diving Bell and the Butterflyâ (2007) and the James Bond film âQuantum of Solaceâ (2008). âHe has a politeness of simplicity, that is the most difficult thing to do, but he grabs really deep the soul of all human beings.â</p>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><div class="thumb"><img alt="Cannes Film Festival" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/05/16/movies/cannes-image/cannes-image-blogSmallThumb.jpg" width="50" height="50"></div><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/category/cannes-film-festival/">Cannes Film Festival</a></h6><p class="summary">Features, news, interviews and more.</p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For âThe Blue Room,â his second film as director to be shown at Cannes (after âOn Tourâ in 2010), Mr. Amalric and his co-writer and co-star, Stephanie Cleau, translated the Belgian crime novelistâs economy of language into an economy of images. They wrote some cuts into the script, others were done by the editor, FranÃ§ois Gedigier. âIt was like music, like free jazz,â Mr. Amalric said.</p>
<div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h6 class="kicker">Cannes: A Critic&#8217;s View</h6>
<p class="summary">Perspectives on the festival from The Times&#8217;s co-chief film critic Manohla Dargis.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/20/cannes-film-festival-the-dogs-of-white-god/">The Dogs of âWhite Godâ</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/movies/red-army-is-among-the-notables-at-festival.html">âRed Armyâ Is Among the Notables at Festival</a></li>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/05/16/movies/sommeliers-decanting-the-madness-of-cannes.html">The Madness of Cannes</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The film tells the story of an extramarital affair between Julien (Mr. Amalric) and Esther (Ms. Cleau, a playwright and screenwriter who makes her film debut here) that ends in murder, but who did it? Both are put on trial for the killing of Julienâs wife, Delphine (LÃ©a Drucker). For the production, they held a trial, inviting the public to be unpaid extras.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over the course of the film, Julien becomes increasingly paranoid. Mr. Amalric said he built the role on ambiguities. âYou think itâs not him, but I hope people are always asking themselves questions,â he said. During the trial, all eyes are on Esther. Did she do it? âIt may be possible that she is just a woman in love,â Mr. Amalric said. âAnd a woman in love is dangerous.â</p>
	</div>
